One question is: If you disguise your voice in order to impersonate a custo=
mer executive on a due diligence call in order to trick a=C2=A0potential in=
vestor into giving your company money,  is that securities fraud? I am not =
really a lawyer and nothing in this column is ever legal advice but =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0yes? Yes, that does seem very much like the core of securities fra=
ud? Lying to people about your business in order to trick them into investi=
ng money in your securities? So I=E2=80=99m going to go with yes.Another qu=
estion is: If you do that,=C2=A0and it doesn=E2=80=99t work, and then you d=
on=E2=80=99t=C2=A0disclose=C2=A0to a=C2=A0different=C2=A0potential investor=
 that you tried that on the first investor, is=C2=A0that=C2=A0securities fr=
aud? That is, once you=E2=80=99ve done the fake diligence call, is every=C2=
=A0subsequent=C2=A0stock sale=C2=A0also=C2=A0fraud unless you say =E2=80=9C=
hey guys, just so you know, we tried a little fraud before but now we have =
stopped=E2=80=9D?It is a little harsh but I think the answer is also yes? I=
 am talking of course about Ozy Media, whose co-founder Samir Rao allegedly=
 impersonated a YouTube executive on a due diligence=C2=A0call with potenti=
al investors from Goldman Sachs Group Inc. about how Ozy=E2=80=99s videos d=
o on YouTube. Goldman quickly figured it out and passed on the investment s=
o, no harm no foul I guess? Goldman did not sue anyway, though apparently G=
oogle (which owns YouTube) found out about the impersonation and reported i=
t to the FBI. But then Ozy kept going around trying to raise money, and it =
succeeded, and  one of its later investors has now sued:Ozy Media Inc. was =
sued by an investor over its co-founder=E2=80=99s impersonation of a YouTub=
e executive during a conference call with Goldman Sachs Group Inc. executiv=
es about a potential investment.LifeLine Legacy Holdings LLC said in a secu=
rities fraud suit filed late Monday that it invested around $2.25 million i=
n Ozy in February and May partly because co-founders Carlos Watson and Sami=
r Rao claimed Goldman was about to put money in the company.=E2=80=9CWatson=
 and Rao expressly represented to LifeLine that Goldman Sachs was positioni=
ng itself to make a substantial investment in the company,=E2=80=9D Beverly=
 Hills-based LifeLine said in its complaint filed in federal court in San J=
ose. =E2=80=A6Ozy never disclosed that =E2=80=9CRao attempted to impersonat=
e an executive of YouTube in an effort to obtain a substantial investment f=
rom Goldman Sachs, or that, as a result of Rao=E2=80=99s fraudulent conduct=
, Goldman Sachs declined to invest in Ozy Media and that Ozy Media was unde=
r investigation by government agencies,=E2=80=9D LifeLine said in its suit.=
Did it have to disclose that? Ozy is a private company, and when it sold st=
ock to LifeLine it did so under a stock purchase agreement, and a stock pur=
chase agreement will generally contain a representation saying something li=
ke =E2=80=9Cthe company complies with all applicable laws,=E2=80=9D and if =
you are currently doing a fraud, or recently got finished doing a fraud, th=
at rep is probably not true. Which makes the new sale, arguably, also a fra=
ud. From LifeLine=E2=80=99s complaint:Based, in part, upon the foregoing re=
presentations, on or about February 24, 2021, LifeLine entered into a Serie=
s C Stock Purchase Agreement (=E2=80=9CSeries C SPA=E2=80=9D) pursuant to w=
hich it agreed to purchase approximately $2 million of Series C Preferred S=
hares in Ozy Media.Among other things, the Series C SPA provided that =E2=
=80=9Cto the Company=E2=80=99s knowledge, the Company is not in violation o=
f any federal or state statute, rule or regulation applicable to the Compan=
y=E2=80=9D.In hindsight the proper approach would have been for Ozy=E2=80=
=99s lawyers to edit that rep to say =E2=80=9Cto the Company=E2=80=99s know=
ledge, the Company is not in violation of any federal or state statute, rul=
e or regulation applicable to the Company; provided, however, that an execu=
tive of the Company did disguise his voice on a call with another potential=
=C2=A0investor to impersonate a YouTube executive, which ended up getting r=
eported to the FBI, but that investor never actually invested and the execu=
tive was having a tough time so we think it=E2=80=99s not really a big deal=
, but just FYI.=E2=80=9D That would have been fine I think. Though of cours=
e then LifeLine probably wouldn=E2=80=99t have invested? Which is the point=
? The point is that this would have been material to LifeLine=E2=80=99s inv=
estment decision, had Ozy told them about it?=C2=A0Another question is: Doe=
s Ozy exist, or what? Ozy announced last Friday that it had shut down, but =
then its chief executive officer did a round of television interviews Monda=
y and Tuesday saying actually nope it=E2=80=99s back. Arguably it is a plea=
sant state for Ozy to be in, sort of shut down and sort of not. Do they get=
 to choose from moment to moment which it is? Go on TV: =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=
=99re back and better than ever.=E2=80=9D Leave the set and get served with=
 a lawsuit: =E2=80=9CNo no no no no, there=E2=80=99s no such thing as Ozy M=
edia, it=E2=80=99s gone, poof.=E2=80=9D Maybe Ozy continues to exist as a b=
rand but not as a defendant in securities lawsuits?
