      Robinhood vs. the SEC
   =20
 =20
My rough, inaccurate-but-useful model of Robinhood Markets Inc. is:=09It is=
 a big retail brokerage that has done a lot to change investing over the pa=
st few years and is one of the most important companies in the financial in=
dustry, but=09Nobody who works there has ever met a securities lawyer.Not f=
air, I know! (Its general counsel actually used to be an SEC commissioner?)=
 And yet. The scandals that it keeps having are=C2=A0weird, like, just one =
level more=C2=A0amateurish than the scandals that=C2=A0other important=C2=
=A0financial firms have. It once announced that it would give its customers=
 bank accounts, but then various regulators called it up and said =E2=80=9C=
uh you=E2=80=99re not a bank?=E2=80=9D and by the=C2=A0next day=C2=A0it had=
  pulled the product. Its great business innovation was to=C2=A0creatively =
use=C2=A0payment-for-order-flow revenue to subsidize commission-free tradin=
g in a way that was both commercially successful for Robinhood and also pro=
bably good for most of its customers, but instead of advertising that smart=
 move it  spent years lying about it and got in trouble with the Securities=
 and Exchange Commission.=C2=A0This summer the Financial Industry Regulator=
y Authority=C2=A0fined Robinhood $57 million, =E2=80=9Cthe largest financia=
l penalty ever ordered by FINRA,=E2=80=9D largely for  having a bad website=
. Big financial institutions get in trouble all the time for scandals of th=
e form =E2=80=9Cwe saw a chance to make money at the expense of our custome=
rs, and we took it,=E2=80=9D but each of Robinhood=E2=80=99s scandals feels=
 like they are just confused about what they=E2=80=99re doing.Anyway I thou=
ght about that model as I read this absolutely wild comment letter from Rob=
inhood to the SEC. Here=E2=80=99s how Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Annie Massa =
and Misyrlena Egkolfopoulou  describe it:Robinhood Markets Inc. fired a war=
ning shot to regulators, saying efforts to impose new rules on online broke=
rages=E2=80=99 engagement with customers would face a high legal burden and=
 could ultimately be rejected by U.S. courts.=C2=A0In a 27-page letter to t=
he Securities and Exchange Commission, Robinhood laid out a number of argum=
ents for why it will be hard to justify enhanced oversight. The SEC is exam=
ining whether notifications, lists of popular stocks and a variety of game-=
like features used by Robinhood and other brokerage apps are encouraging ex=
cessive trading that puts retail investors at risk.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThe botto=
m line is that additional regulation in this area will undoubtedly raise si=
gnificant legal issues,=E2=80=9D Robinhood Financial President David Dussea=
ult wrote in the letter, which was posted on the SEC=E2=80=99s website Tues=
day.=C2=A0Robinhood said its mobile app isn=E2=80=99t a game, noting that i=
n contrast to some of its competitors, it doesn=E2=80=99t use tactics such =
as leader boards or trading competitions to keep users coming back. Moreove=
r, the brokerage argued, attempts to hem in digital engagement with brokera=
ge apps could violate free-speech protections.Yes look right that=E2=80=99s=
 a thing, that is absolutely a thing that people sometimes say, =E2=80=9Cse=
curities regulation is unconstitutional because the First Amendment protect=
s my right to tell you about this stock I like.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s not =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s just that if you went to a securities lawyer an=
d asked them to draft a comment letter to the SEC they might write somethin=
g different? Like, my sense is that the SEC thinks that it has fairly compl=
ete power to regulate=C2=A0how broker-dealers communicate with their custom=
ers about investing, and if you disagree you will have to take it up with a=
 judge, not send the SEC a letter saying =E2=80=9Cfree speech, man.=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t know. There=E2=80=99s five pages in the letter abo=
ut the First Amendment.But there=E2=80=99s also five pages about the Admini=
strative Procedure Act! The APA is sort of the backdrop to most of the U.S.=
 regulatory state; it says that when a regulator wants to make new rules, i=
t has to follow certain procedures and build a record demonstrating why the=
 rule is necessary and appropriate. Later, if someone doesn=E2=80=99t like =
a rule, they can go to court, and the court will consider whether the regul=
atory agency followed the procedures or whether the rule was =E2=80=9Carbit=
rary and capricious.=E2=80=9D Part of the reason the SEC has  asked for com=
ments on brokerages=E2=80=99 digital engagement practices is because that i=
s a step required by the APA: Before making a rule, agencies are supposed t=
o gather evidence and public input. (To be clear, that is the only=C2=A0maj=
or step the SEC has taken; it has not proposed any new digital engagement r=
ules yet.) Robinhood=E2=80=99s discussion of the APA is basically of the fo=
rm =E2=80=9Cif you don=E2=80=99t follow the law, we will sue you for not fo=
llowing the law.=E2=80=9D Which is true of every rule-making by every agenc=
y and just a weird threat to make? Like, yes, the SEC is aware that it has =
to follow the proper procedures when it makes new rules. Spending=C2=A0five=
 pages=C2=A0reminding the SEC of that seems tone-deaf and antagonistic. A s=
ample:Second, and closely related to the SEC=E2=80=99s obligation to demons=
trate an actual need for additional regulation, the SEC will need comprehen=
sively and thoughtfully to examine existing regulations of broker-dealers a=
nd investment advisers and to explain why those protections are sufficient =
or not to accomplish the SEC=E2=80=99s purported regulatory objectives.=C2=
=A0As detailed above, customer engagement practices, now manifesting as dig=
ital engagement practices, not new and they are already subject to signific=
ant existing regulatory controls designed to protect retail investors.=C2=
=A0Before the SEC rushes to impose new and costly regulatory mandates on th=
e market, the SEC must analyze this =E2=80=9Cexisting regime=E2=80=9D and d=
etermine whether =E2=80=9Csufficient protections=E2=80=9D already exist.=C2=
=A0=C2=A0A =E2=80=9Cfailure to analyze=E2=80=9D carefully existing regulati=
ons would render any SEC final regulation =E2=80=9Carbitrary and capricious=
.=E2=80=9DWhat? Yes, right, if the SEC makes a new rule saying =E2=80=9Cbro=
kerage firms can=E2=80=99t show confetti in their mobile apps to celebrate =
customer trades,=E2=80=9D it will have to put out a 200-page notice explain=
ing that confetti is bad, and that there is not currently a rule against co=
nfetti, and that the only way to get rid of confetti is by making a new rul=
e against confetti, and that the new rule is reasonably designed to restric=
t confetti,=C2=A0and that the costs of complying with the rule are reasonab=
le measured against the benefits of the rule, and a bunch of other stuff. T=
here is a lot of apparatus involved. But this=C2=A0is not news to the SEC! =
It knows all of this! It employs whole lawyers to make sure it follows its =
legal obligations! Does Robinhood?Here is what I think is going on here. Th=
ere is a perception in the financial industry that Gary Gensler, the still-=
somewhat-new chair of the SEC, wants to dramatically remake all sorts of=C2=
=A0rules=C2=A0in ways that will be broadly bad for the industry, that he wa=
nts to tear up well-settled expectations and do something completely new. I=
f Gensler is going to ban confetti and gamification and payment for order f=
low and make new rules about climate disclosure and limit private-equity co=
nflicts of interest and crack down on crypto exchanges and do 9,000 other t=
hings to reshape the financial landscape, he=E2=80=99s going to be=C2=A0bus=
y. His SEC will need to move faster than the SEC usually does; the changes =
will be both more drastic=C2=A0and faster than the typical new SEC rules.[2=
] There is I think some nervous expectation that it will be a =E2=80=9Cmove=
 fast and break things=E2=80=9D sort of SEC. Part of the reason the SEC usu=
ally moves slowly and deliberately is because of all those APA procedures; =
if it wants to make radical changes quickly then it might cut corners on th=
ose procedures.Meanwhile of course Robinhood is very much a =E2=80=9Cmove f=
ast and break things=E2=80=9D sort of brokerage, which is also frowned upon=
. At some point there is likely to be some controversy=C2=A0between Robinho=
od and the SEC in which the SEC says =E2=80=9CRobinhood are some lawless ho=
oligans=E2=80=9D and Robinhood says =E2=80=9Cactually the SEC are some lawl=
ess hooligans.=E2=80=9D[3] It does make some sense for Robinhood to get a j=
ump on that. Sending a letter to the SEC saying =E2=80=9Cif you break the l=
aw we=E2=80=99ll sue you for breaking the law=E2=80=9D is, in ordinary circ=
umstances, bizarrely pointless and confrontational, but if there=E2=80=99s =
going to be a confrontation anyway Robinhood might as well strike first.In =
other news:Helplines of gambling addiction recovery groups have been ringin=
g with a new kind of caller: day traders.The rise of mobile brokerage appli=
cations outfitted with prompts, animations, rewards and digital flourishes =
have brought the feel of investing platforms closer to online sports bettin=
g and gambling.=E2=80=9CThe user experience is converging and the line betw=
een gambling and investing, which was already pretty fluid, has almost been=
 completely erased,=E2=80=9D said Keith Whyte, executive director of the Na=
tional Council on Problem Gambling, among the groups reporting more calls f=
rom stock traders to their help lines. =E2=80=A6The fusion of stock trading=
 with game-like features has gained attention as a new generation of invest=
ors flocked to the market during the pandemic. While gambling carries a cul=
tural stigma, new investors on brokerage apps are vulnerable because they =
=E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t see themselves as gambling=E2=80=9D, Whyte said.Feli=
cia Grondin, acting executive director of the Council on Compulsive Gamblin=
g of New Jersey, said the absence of other things to bet on, such as sports=
 and horseracing, in the early days of the pandemic pushed some gamblers in=
to stock trading platforms that can deliver the same thrill. Her group=E2=
=80=99s 1-800-Gambler helpline has received an almost 50 per cent increase =
in calls related to day trading since the start of the pandemic, she said, =
though she noted that the volume was small compared to calls about lotterie=
s and sports betting.
