   =20
 =20
Here is a fantastic=C2=A0New York Times magazine story about the meaning of=
 art and friendship that I want to mention here because it is also about th=
e discovery of private electronic communications in litigation. Basically e=
veryone knows that if you work at a financial institution, and your employe=
r gets sued or investigated by authorities for something you did, your emai=
ls and electronic chats will be turned over in the course of litigation, an=
d the person suing you will get all the records of you saying =E2=80=9Chaha=
ha lets rip these muppets=E2=80=99s faces off=E2=80=9D or whatever, and tha=
t will be read back to you in court and you=E2=80=99ll be like =E2=80=9Cit =
was a joke?=E2=80=9D and the jury will all glare at you. That is how litiga=
tion works in the U.S.: Each side gets to ask the other side to produce all=
 of its internal communications concerning the trade, and then there is a l=
ot of wrangling and a lot of legal bills, and then the communications get t=
urned over, and each side gets to mine the other side=E2=80=99s chats and e=
mails for embarrassing evidence. And every financial professional=C2=A0know=
s this at=C2=A0some=C2=A0level, but they forget it from moment to moment, w=
hich is why those emails and chats keep getting written and produced in dis=
covery and read in court.=C2=A0Fine! But what is less obvious is that, if y=
ou=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0work at a financial institution, if you are just=
 a person, and you get sued=C2=A0personally=C2=A0by someone in your social =
circle whom you don=E2=80=99t particularly like,=C2=A0you might have to tur=
n over all your emails and group chats about that person in discovery?=C2=
=A0This particular story is about a writer named Sonya Larson who wrote a s=
hort story that takes some elements from the life and personality of anothe=
r writer named Dawn Dorland who was in a Facebook group with her. Things es=
calate, Dorland sues Larson for copyright infringement, and Larson sues Dor=
land for defamation. And this happens:The litigation crept along quietly un=
til earlier this year, when the discovery phase uncorked something unexpect=
ed =E2=80=94 a trove of documents that seemed to recast the conflict in an =
entirely new way. There, in black and white, were pages and pages of printe=
d texts and emails between Larson and her writer friends, gossiping about D=
orland and deriding everything about her =E2=80=94 not just her claim of be=
ing appropriated but the way she talked publicly about her kidney donation.=
What a terrifying paragraph! The lesson here is either (1) don=E2=80=99t go=
ssip about your frenemies by text or email or (2) arrange your life so that=
 you never sue, and are never sued by, the people you talk trash about in t=
exts and emails. (Or for that matter the people who talk trash about you in=
 texts and emails =E2=80=94=C2=A0reading=C2=A0this stuff can=E2=80=99t be a=
ny fun either.)=C2=A0I think for most people option (2) will be easier.
