<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">24/7 trading</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic situation of U.S. equity mar=
ket structure is:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 4=
0px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Big institutiona=
l investors want to be able to buy or sell large chunks of stock quickly wi=
thout moving the price. The best way to do this is to coordinate around liq=
uidity: If I want to buy, I want to buy when everyone else is selling; if w=
e all pick one 15-minute period to do our trading, there will be lots of bu=
yers and lots of sellers and we=E2=80=99ll all be able to do big trades at =
a fair market price.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Small retail =
day traders want to finish work at 5 p.m., go out for a few beers, come hom=
e, have dinner, watch some TV, have a few more beers, and then at around 10=
 p.m. they want to fire up their computer and spend six hours trading GameS=
top stock and posting about it on Reddit.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom=
: 5px;">Foreign investors want to be able to trade U.S. stocks during <em>t=
heir</em> business hours.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">What act=
ually happens is that the stock market is continuously open from 9:30 a.m. =
to 4 p.m. New York time Monday through Friday, with some less-liquid extend=
ed hours in the morning and evening.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
That doesn=E2=80=99t serve anyone! I have in the past <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25254005.273335/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21=
iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDItMDYvdGVzbGEtaGFzLXNvbWUtd2lsZC=
10aW1lcw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBebd1d5ed" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> argued</a>, with a <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25254005.273335/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDMtMDkvc3R1ZmYt=
aXMtYmFkLXNvLXN0b2Nrcy1hcmUtZG93bg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB428e867d" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;"> certain</a> amount of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/25254005.273335/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGl=
jbGVzLzIwMjAtMDEtMjgvZmFrZS1zb2xhci1nZW5lcmF0b3JzLWdlbmVyYXRlZC1mYWtlLXRheC=
1icmVha3M/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB74a38d0f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> seriousness</a>, that=
 the stock market should have much, much shorter hours; 15 or 30 minutes a =
day should suffice for everyone who wants liquidity to find it, and traders=
 could spend the rest of their days researching companies or writing market=
 analyses or reading poetry or hanging out with their families. But you cou=
ld <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25254005.273335=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9pcy10aGUtc3RvY2stbWFya2V0LW9wZW4tYX=
QtMy1hLW0tdGhpcy1zdGFydHVwLXNheXMtaXQtc2hvdWxkLWJlLTExNjMzNDMxNjAy/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB028b6865" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;">take it the other way</a>:</p><blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A startup trading platform is seeking approv=
al from the Securities and Exchange Commission to launch the first U.S. sto=
ck exchange that would operate around the clock, including on weekends and =
holidays.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The startup, 24 Exchange, said it=
 filed key parts of its application for a national stock-exchange license w=
ith the SEC on Monday, including a rulebook and user manual detailing its p=
roposed approach to trading hours.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Under de=
cades-old conventions, the bulk of stock trading takes place between 9:30 a=
.m. and 4 p.m. ET on weekdays, and exchanges shut down for holidays, such a=
s Good Friday and Washington=E2=80=99s Birthday. In contrast, 24 Exchange w=
ould operate like the foreign-exchange and cryptocurrency markets, which ru=
n continuously.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The three-year-old startup =
already offers trading in FX and crypto. Its parent company, 24 Exchange Be=
rmuda Ltd., is incorporated in Bermuda, but the proposed stock exchange wou=
ld be run by a U.S. subsidiary. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I=
n an interview, Mr. Galinov said there is growing demand for round-the-cloc=
k stock trading from individual investors. Not only do such investors often=
 want to buy or sell stocks outside of standard trading hours, but the 24/7=
 nature of crypto has raised expectations that stocks should work the same =
way, he said.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIf there is big news=
 over the weekend, you can try to trade, but you really can=E2=80=99t,=E2=
=80=9D the founder and chief executive said.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">He says that the growing demand for round-the-clock trading =
comes from individual investors, who trade as a hobby after their workday i=
s over and who want more time to do that.=C2=A0<em>Professional=C2=A0</em>i=
nvestors trade as a job during the workday and presumably want=C2=A0<em>les=
s=C2=A0</em>time to do that, not only so that they can spend more time with=
 their families,[1] but also so that they can source as much liquidity as p=
ossible when they do trade.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And in fa=
ct it is already fairly easy for professional traders to coordinate around =
prime times for liquidity: A disproportionate amount of the trading in U.S.=
 stock markets <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/252=
54005.273335/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvOWUxZjA1YjQtNDNlNy0xMWU4LT=
gwM2EtMjk1Yzk3ZTZmZDBi/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB98a0c8ae" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">happens i=
n the few minutes</a> around the opening and (especially) the closing of th=
e trading day. If you are an index fund looking to buy or sell a bunch of s=
tock while tracking the index, you will have a tendency to buy or sell all =
your stock at the 4 p.m. close, because the closing price is in a sense the=
 =E2=80=9Cofficial=E2=80=9D price of the day and matching that price lines =
up with your index. If you are anyone else looking to buy or sell a bunch o=
f stock, you want to trade when everyone else is trading, and that happens =
to be at the close (when the people looking to match the closing price=C2=
=A0are trading). And so liquidity is concentrated at the close, and =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0as Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Larry Tabb <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/25254005.273335/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9sdGFiYi=
9zdGF0dXMvMTQ0NTQ3MjY5NDk3NjIyMTE5MD9zPTEx/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB35cf52c=
2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">tweeted</a> =E2=80=94=C2=A0professional traders =E2=80=9Ccan d=
o errands in the middle of the day.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">But if you are a hobbyist day trader,=C2=A04 p.m. is not a particularly c=
onvenient time to trade stocks, so you want to be able to trade all night. =
And you probably do not need to have a giant index fund on the other side o=
f your trades because (1) you aren=E2=80=99t trading in huge size and (2) y=
ou kind of=C2=A0<em>want=C2=A0</em>the market to be volatile? Like, you are=
 trading for fun. If the stock goes up 10% every time someone buys 100 shar=
es, and then down 10% every time someone sells, that is more fun than if it=
 just sits there.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The synthesis is pr=
obably a short deep liquid session for professionals and a long strange ill=
iquid fun session for retail, like:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decima=
l; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;=
">You can trade stocks 24/7.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Insti=
tutional investors don=E2=80=99t, and do most of their trading in a 15- or =
30-minute period leading up to 4 p.m. New York time.</li>=09<li style=3D"ma=
rgin-bottom: 5px;">The rest of the time the market is weird, volatile and r=
etail-driven.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you are making ma=
rkets for retail at 3 a.m. you can probably charge them a pretty wide sprea=
d, because they=E2=80=99re not there for tight seamless execution, they=E2=
=80=99re there for a good time.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So ye=
ah I guess I come down in favor of both 15 minutes a day of trading and als=
o 24 hours a day? Still I feel like allowing the 24 Exchange is kind of rou=
gh on everyone?=C2=A0If you are a stock trader and there is a U.S. exchange=
 open 24 hours, sometimes news will happen at midnight, or a buyer in Hong =
Kong will do a big trade and move the stock, and you=E2=80=99ll have to kee=
p up to speed on it. Seems exhausting. Also if you are a=C2=A0<em>company</=
em>=C2=A0looking to announce a merger or earnings or other big news, it is =
convenient to be able to do it outside of trading hours; if all hours are t=
rading hours then everything gets a bit more difficult.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">Also this is cool:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>24 Exchange is also seeking the SEC=E2=80=99s permission to allow fraction=
al trading on its proposed stock exchange in increments of as little as 1/1=
000th of a share.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=
=99t know what that means, exactly, but I suppose if a brokerage can sell y=
ou a fraction of a share then so can a stock exchange. (Since fractions of =
a share <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25254005.2=
73335/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMTAtM=
TgvaGFsZi1hLXNoYXJlLW9mLXN0b2NrLWlzLWJldHRlci10aGFuLW5vdGhpbmc/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cBbf26b06a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;"> don=E2=80=99t generally =E2=80=9Cexist=E2=
=80=9D</a> as a matter of corporate law or the company=E2=80=99s shareholde=
r register, you need some entity to hold the remaining 999/1000th of a shar=
e if you sell a customer 1/1000th, but if Robinhood can find some entity to=
 do that then why can=E2=80=99t an exchange?) This is another crypto-influe=
nced development: Cryptocurrencies are transferable in tiny fractions and s=
o people expect to be able to do the same with stocks; right now brokerages=
 let them do that in some approximate way, but it makes sense that it would=
 become more standard until eventually it is seamless and companies think n=
othing of paying someone a bonus of 102.739 shares of stock.</p><table clas=
