=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> having a bad website</a>. Big financial inst=
itutions get in trouble all the time for scandals of the form =E2=80=9Cwe s=
aw a chance to make money at the expense of our customers, and we took it,=
=E2=80=9D but each of Robinhood=E2=80=99s scandals feels like they are just=
 confused about what they=E2=80=99re doing.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Anyway I thought about that model as I read <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/25254005.273335/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9jb21t=
ZW50cy9zNy0xMC0yMS9zNzEwMjEtOTMxNjQ5OC0yNjAwOTIucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB89e7271c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">this absolutely wild comment letter</a> from Robinhood=
 to the SEC. Here=E2=80=99s how Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Annie Massa and Mi=
syrlena Egkolfopoulou <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/25254005.273335/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzI=
wMjEtMTAtMDUvcm9iaW5ob29kLXNheXMtc2VjLWZhY2VzLWhpZ2gtbGVnYWwtYnVyZGVuLWZvci=
1icm9rZXItYXBwLXJ1bGVz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB62506b7c" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> describe=
 it</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Robinhood Markets Inc.=
 fired a warning shot to regulators, saying efforts to impose new rules on =
online brokerages=E2=80=99 engagement with customers would face a high lega=
l burden and could ultimately be rejected by U.S. courts.=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a 27-page letter to the Securities and Exchange Com=
mission, Robinhood laid out a number of arguments for why it will be hard t=
o justify enhanced oversight. The SEC is examining whether notifications, l=
ists of popular stocks and a variety of game-like features used by Robinhoo=
d and other brokerage apps are encouraging excessive trading that puts reta=
il investors at risk.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe bo=
ttom line is that additional regulation in this area will undoubtedly raise=
 significant legal issues,=E2=80=9D Robinhood Financial President David Dus=
seault wrote in the letter, which was posted on the SEC=E2=80=99s website T=
uesday.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Robinhood said its mobile app=
 isn=E2=80=99t a game, noting that in contrast to some of its competitors, =
it doesn=E2=80=99t use tactics such as leader boards or trading competition=
s to keep users coming back. Moreover, the brokerage argued, attempts to he=
m in digital engagement with brokerage apps could violate free-speech prote=
ctions.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes look right that=E2=
=80=99s a thing, that is absolutely a thing that people sometimes say, =E2=
=80=9Csecurities regulation is unconstitutional because the First Amendment=
 protects my right to tell you about this stock I like.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=
=99s not =E2=80=A6=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s just that if you went to a securities =
lawyer and asked them to draft a comment letter to the SEC they might write=
 something different? Like, my sense is that the SEC thinks that it has fai=
rly complete power to regulate=C2=A0<em>how broker-dealers communicate with=
 their customers about investing</em>, and if you disagree you will have to=
 take it up with a judge, not send the SEC a letter saying =E2=80=9Cfree sp=
eech, man.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t know. There=E2=80=99s five pages i=
n the letter about the First Amendment.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But=
 there=E2=80=99s also five pages about the Administrative Procedure Act! Th=
e APA is sort of the backdrop to most of the U.S. regulatory state; it says=
 that when a regulator wants to make new rules, it has to follow certain pr=
ocedures and build a record demonstrating why the rule is necessary and app=
ropriate. Later, if someone doesn=E2=80=99t like a rule, they can go to cou=
rt, and the court will consider whether the regulatory agency followed the =
procedures or whether the rule was =E2=80=9Carbitrary and capricious.=E2=80=
=9D Part of the reason the SEC has <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/25254005.273335/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW=
9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDgtMzAvZXNnLWFjY291bnRpbmctcmVxdWlyZXMtYWNjb3VudGFud=
HM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1d39efce" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> asked for comments on broker=
ages=E2=80=99 digital engagement practices</a> is because that is a step re=
quired by the APA: Before making a rule, agencies are supposed to gather ev=
idence and public input. (To be clear, that is the <em>only=C2=A0</em>major=
 step the SEC has taken; it has not proposed any new digital engagement rul=
es yet.) Robinhood=E2=80=99s discussion of the APA is basically of the form=
 =E2=80=9Cif you don=E2=80=99t follow the law, we will sue you for not foll=
owing the law.=E2=80=9D Which is true of every rule-making by every agency =
and just a weird threat to make? Like, yes, the SEC is aware that it has to=
 follow the proper procedures when it makes new rules. Spending=C2=A0<em>fi=
ve pages=C2=A0</em>reminding the SEC of that seems tone-deaf and antagonist=
ic. A sample:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em><strong>Secon=
d</strong></em>, and closely related to the SEC=E2=80=99s obligation to dem=
onstrate an actual need for additional regulation, the SEC will need compre=
hensively and thoughtfully to examine existing regulations of broker-dealer=
s and investment advisers and to explain why those protections are sufficie=
nt or not to accomplish the SEC=E2=80=99s purported regulatory objectives.=
=C2=A0As detailed above, customer engagement practices, now manifesting as =
digital engagement practices, not new and they are already subject to signi=
ficant existing regulatory controls designed to protect retail investors.=
=C2=A0Before the SEC rushes to impose new and costly regulatory mandates on=
 the market, the SEC must analyze this =E2=80=9Cexisting regime=E2=80=9D an=
d determine whether =E2=80=9Csufficient protections=E2=80=9D already exist.=
=C2=A0=C2=A0A =E2=80=9Cfailure to analyze=E2=80=9D carefully existing regul=
ations would render any SEC final regulation =E2=80=9Carbitrary and caprici=
ous.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What? Yes, right=
, if the SEC makes a new rule saying =E2=80=9Cbrokerage firms can=E2=80=99t=
 show confetti in their mobile apps to celebrate customer trades,=E2=80=9D =
it will have to put out a 200-page notice explaining that confetti is bad, =
and that there is not currently a rule against confetti, and that the only =
way to get rid of confetti is by making a new rule against confetti, and th=
at the new rule is reasonably designed to restrict confetti,=C2=A0and that =
the costs of complying with the rule are reasonable measured against the be=
nefits of the rule, and a bunch of other stuff. There is a lot of apparatus=
 involved. But this=C2=A0is not news to the SEC! It knows all of this! It e=
mploys whole lawyers to make sure it follows its legal obligations! Does Ro=
binhood?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is what I think is going on h=
ere. There is a perception in the financial industry that Gary Gensler, the=
